788,"approvedByContent":789,"correspondence":790,"equalContribution":791,"presentAddress":19,"other":792},[732],{"loopId":733,"fullName":734,"textContent":735},"558569","Igor Diemberger","\r\n            Edited by:\r\n            Igor Diemberger, University of Bologna, Italy",[737,739,752],{"#text":738},"\n          ",{"p":740},[741,743,750],{"#text":742},"\n            \n            ",{"ext-link":744,":@":746},[745],{"#text":734},{"@_ext-link-type":747,"@_xmlns:xlink":748,"@_xlink:href":749},"uri","http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink","https://loop.frontiersin.org/people/558569/overview",{"#text":751},", University of Bologna, Italy",{"#text":753},"\n        ",[755,759],{"loopId":756,"fullName":757,"textContent":758},"1078366","Guillermo Alberto Keller","\r\n            Reviewed by:\r\n            Guillermo Alberto Keller, Universidad de Buenos Aires, Argentina",{"loopId":760,"fullName":761,"textContent":762},"1520262","Bidita Khandelwal","\r\n            Bidita Khandelwal, Sikkim Manipal University, India",[764,765,775,776,787],{"#text":738},{"p":766},[767,768,773],{"#text":742},{"ext-link":769,":@":771},[770],{"#text":757},{"@_ext-link-type":747,"@_xmlns:xlink":748,"@_xlink:href":772},"https://loop.frontiersin.org/people/1078366/overview",{"#text":774},", Universidad de Buenos Aires, Argentina",{"#text":738},{"p":777},[778,780,785],{"#text":779},"\n            ",{"ext-link":781,":@":783},[782],{"#text":761},{"@_ext-link-type":747,"@_xlink:href":784},"https://loop.frontiersin.org/people/1520262/overview",{"#text":786},", Sikkim Manipal University, India",{"#text":753},[],[],"*Correspondence: Clair Blacketer, bWJsYWNrZUBpdHMuam5qLmNvbQ==",[],[793,794,798],{"#text":738},{"p":795},[796],{"#text":797},"This article was submitted to Cardiovascular Drug Safety, a section of the journal Frontiers in Drug Safety and Regulation",{"#text":753},"2022-10-19","2022-09-22","2022-09-01",{"copyrightStatement":803,"copyrightYear":804,"copyrightHolder":805,"licenseUrl":806,"licenseText":807},"Copyright © 2022 Blacketer, Reps, Wang, Ryan and Yuan.",2022,"Blacketer, Reps, Wang, Ryan and Yuan","http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/",[808,809,820],{"#text":738},{"p":810},[811,813,818],{"#text":812},"This is an open-access article distributed under the terms of the ",{"ext-link":814,":@":817},[815],{"#text":816},"Creative Commons Attribution License (CC BY)",{"@_ext-link-type":747,"@_xlink:href":806},{"#text":819},". The use, distribution or reproduction in other forums is permitted, provided the original author(s) and the copyright owner(s) are credited and that the original publication in this journal is cited, in accordance with accepted academic practice. No use, distribution or reproduction is permitted which does not comply with these terms.",{"#text":753},[822,825,827,829,831],[823],{"#text":824},"prediction model",[826],{"#text":462},[828],{"#text":463},[830],{"#text":464},[832],{"#text":833},"validation",[],[836,837,857],{"#text":753},{"p":838},[839,841,845,847,850,852,855],{"#text":840},"When developing predictive models, model simplicity and performance often need to be balanced. We propose a novel methodology to put the performance of bleeding risk prediction models ORBIT, ATRIA, HAS-BLED, CHADS",{"sub":842},[843],{"#text":844},"2,",{"#text":846}," and CHA",{"sub":848},[849],{"#text":616},{"#text":851},"DS",{"sub":853},[854],{"#text":616},{"#text":856},"-VASc into perspective. Instead of comparing the existing models’ performance against the 0.5–1 AUROC scale, we suggest estimating a prediction task specific AUROC scale, lower bound AUROC (lbAUROC) and upper bound AUROC (ubAUROC), to help assess the balance between model simplicity and performance and determine whether more complex models could significantly improve the ability to predict the outcome. We validate the existing bleeding risk prediction models by applying them to a cohort of new users of warfarin and a cohort of new users of direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) separately, across a set of four observational databases. Then, we develop the lbAUROC-ubAUROC scale by using the validation data to train regularized logistic regression models. The internal validation AUROC of the model that includes only age and gender variables was used to estimate the lbAUROC. The internal validation AUROC of the model that includes thousands of candidate variables was used to estimate the ubAUROC. The age and gender only models achieved AUROCs between 0.50 and 0.56 (lower bound) and the large-scale models achieved AUROCs between 0.67 and 0.72 and between 0.70 and 0.77 (upper bound) within the target cohorts of warfarin new users and DOACs new users, respectively. The AUROC of existing bleeding risk prediction models fall between the upper-bound and lower-bound of predictive models. Our study showed that this context of the predictability of the outcome is essential when evaluating risk prediction models to be administered in actual practice.",{"#text":858},"\n      ",[860,862,1025,1026,2761,2762,3461,3462,3563,3564,3579],{"#text":861},"\n    ",{"sec":863,":@":1023},[864,865,869,870,891,892,982,983,987,988,1017,1018,1022],{"#text":858},{"title":866},[867],{"#text":868},"1 Introduction",{"#text":858},{"p":871},[872,874,881,883,889],{"#text":873},"Atrial fibrillation (AF) is the most common cardiac arrhythmia. Without proper anticoagulant management, patients with AF have an increased risk of stroke by 5-fold (",{"xref":875,":@":878},[876],{"#text":877},"Mant and Edwards, 2010",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":880},"bibr","B11",{"#text":882},"). Vitamin K antagonists (e.g., warfarin) have been the mainstream of prophylactic therapy in reducing the risk of stroke among patients with AF for many decades. While warfarin is highly efficacious, achieving the desired therapeutic effect in routine clinical practice remains challenging because of its highly variable dose response among individuals, drug-drug interactions, and narrow therapeutic window which requires frequent monitoring of coagulation tests (INR) (",{"xref":884,":@":887},[885],{"#text":886},"Lee and Klein, 2013",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":888},"B9",{"#text":890},"). These challenges in part led to the development of new antithrombotic therapies, also known as direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs).",{"#text":858},{"p":893},[894,896,900,902,908,910,916,917,923,924,930,932,938,939,945,946,952,954,957,958,961,962,965,967,973,974,980],{"#text":895},"Based on the pharmacologic mechanism of action, antithrombotic therapies are associated with increased risk of bleeding. In the contemporary clinical trials that investigated DOACs ",{"italic":897},[898],{"#text":899},"versus",{"#text":901}," warfarin for stroke prevention in patients with AF, the rates of major bleeding (MB) for patients treated with warfarin ranged from 3.1 to 3.4 per 100 person years whereas the rates of MB for patients treated with DOACs therapies had a wider range from 1.6 to 3.6 per 100 person-years, which may be in part due to the difference in patient population and therapeutic dose level (",{"xref":903,":@":906},[904],{"#text":905},"Connolly et al., 2009",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":907},"B1",{"#text":909},"; ",{"xref":911,":@":914},[912],{"#text":913},"Granger et al., 2011",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":915},"B8",{"#text":909},{"xref":918,":@":921},[919],{"#text":920},"Patel et al., 2011",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":922},"B14",{"#text":909},{"xref":925,":@":928},[926],{"#text":927},"Giugliano et al., 2013",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":929},"B5",{"#text":931},"). Several score systems have been developed to predict a patient’s risk of bleeding after anticoagulant use, including ORBIT, ATRIA, and HAS-BLED, with HAS-BLED widely recommended for use in clinical practice (",{"xref":933,":@":936},[934],{"#text":935},"Pisters et al., 2010",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":937},"B15",{"#text":909},{"xref":940,":@":943},[941],{"#text":942},"Fang et al., 2011",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":944},"B3",{"#text":909},{"xref":947,":@":950},[948],{"#text":949},"O’Brien et al., 2015",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":951},"B12",{"#text":953},"). In addition, studies have shown that the CHADS",{"sub":955},[956],{"#text":616},{"#text":846},{"sub":959},[960],{"#text":616},{"#text":851},{"sub":963},[964],{"#text":616},{"#text":966},"-VASc score systems, originally used to predict risk of stroke, are also predictive of risk of MB (",{"xref":968,":@":971},[969],{"#text":970},"Gage et al., 2001",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":972},"B4",{"#text":909},{"xref":975,":@":978},[976],{"#text":977},"Lip et al., 2011",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":979},"B10",{"#text":981},"). These existing bleeding risk score systems are simple algorithms containing 5–10 predictors, easily implemented in a clinical setting. Higher scores are associated with a higher risk of future bleeding.",{"#text":858},{"p":984},[985],{"#text":986},"A predictive score’s performance is typically assessed by its discriminative ability and calibration. Discrimination is commonly determined by measuring the area under the receiver operating characteristic (AUROC) curve, a value between 0.5 and 1, where 0.5 corresponds to no discrimination (i.e., a model that randomly predicts risk) and a value of 1 corresponds to perfect discrimination (i.e., a model that assigns a higher score to all patients who subsequently experience the outcome compared to those who do not). Calibration is a metric that determines how accurate the model’s predicted risks are. For example, if a correctly calibrated model predicts a risk of 10% for an outcome of interest, we would expect one out of 10 persons will experience the outcome.",{"#text":858},{"p":989},[990,992,996,997,1003,1004,1008,1009,1015],{"#text":991},"When developing predictive models, simplicity and performance often need to be balanced. The existing bleeding risk scores are relatively simple models with limited numbers of predictors. These models have been evaluated across various patient populations and the AUROCs values were moderate, ranging from 0.60–0.69 (",{"xref":993,":@":995},[994],{"#text":977},{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":979},{"#text":909},{"xref":998,":@":1001},[999],{"#text":1000},"Goodman et al., 2014",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":1002},"B6",{"#text":909},{"xref":1005,":@":1007},[1006],{"#text":949},{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":951},{"#text":909},{"xref":1010,":@":1013},[1011],{"#text":1012},"Yao et al., 2017",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":1014},"B19",{"#text":1016},"). It is unclear whether the models’ simplicity limited the discriminative ability of these scores and if more complex models, though harder to implement into clinical practice, would significantly improve discriminative ability.",{"#text":858},{"p":1019},[1020],{"#text":1021},"In this study we applied a novel methodology to put the performance of the bleeding risk prediction models into perspective. Instead of comparing the existing models’ discriminations against the 0.5–1 AUROC scale, we estimated a prediction task specific AUROC scale, lower-bound AUROC (lbAUROC) and upper-bound AUROC (ubAUROC), to help assess the balance between model simplicity and discrimination and determine whether the development of more complex models could significantly improve the ability to predict the outcome. We examined whether this novel methodology can be used in validation of predictive models for stroke outcome among patients treated with warfarin and DOACS.",{"#text":861},{"@_id":1024},"s1",{"#text":861},{"sec":1027,":@":2759},[1028,1029,1033,1034,1047,1048,1336,1337,1539,1540,2649,2650,2758],{"#text":858},{"title":1030},[1031],{"#text":1032},"2 Materials and methods",{"#text":858},{"p":1035},[1036,1038,1045],{"#text":1037},"We first validated the existing bleeding risk prediction models by applying them to a set of four databases as listed in ",{"xref":1039,":@":1042},[1040],{"#text":1041},"Section 2.1",{"@_ref-type":1043,"@_rid":1044},"sec","s2-1",{"#text":1046},". We then estimated the lbAUROC by using the validation data to train a regularized logistic regression that includes only age and gender variables, with the internal validation AUROC becoming the lbAUROC. Similarly, the ubAUROC is estimated by using the validation data to train a regularized logistic regression that includes thousands of candidate variables. If the models’ AUROCs are closer to the ubAUROC than the lbAUROC, it indicates a more performant model in terms of discrimination.",{"#text":858},{"sec":1049,":@":1335},[1050,1051,1055,1056,1091,1092,1329,1330,1334],{"#text":753},{"title":1052},[1053],{"#text":1054},"2.1 Datasets",{"#text":753},{"p":1057},[1058,1060,1067,1069,1075,1076,1082,1084,1089],{"#text":1059},"The databases used in this study are described in ",{"xref":1061,":@":1064},[1062],{"#text":1063},"Table 1",{"@_ref-type":1065,"@_rid":1066},"table","T1",{"#text":1068},". All four databases have been standardized into the Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership (OMOP) Common Data Model (CDM), which includes a standard representation of health care experiences (such as information related to drug utilization and condition occurrence), as well as common vocabularies for coding clinical concepts and enables consistent application of analyses across multiple disparate data source (",{"xref":1070,":@":1073},[1071],{"#text":1072},"Voss et al., 2015",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":1074},"B18",{"#text":909},{"xref":1077,":@":1080},[1078],{"#text":1079},"OMOP, 2021",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":1081},"B13",{"#text":1083},"). Complete specifications for the extract, transform, and load (ETL) process for each database is available at: ",{"ext-link":1085,":@":1088},[1086],{"#text":1087},"https://ohdsi.github.io/ETL-LambdaBuilder/",{"@_ext-link-type":747,"@_xmlns:xlink":748,"@_xlink:href":1087},{"#text":1090},".",{"#text":753},{"table-wrap":1093,":@":1327},[1094,1095,1099,1100,1108,1109,1326],{"#text":738},{"label":1096},[1097],{"#text":1098},"TABLE 1",{"#text":738},{"caption":1101},[1102,1103,1107],{"#text":779},{"p":1104},[1105],{"#text":1106},"Description of databases used in the study of AF patients.",{"#text":738},{"#text":738},{"table":1110},[1111,1112,1160,1161,1325],{"#text":779},{"thead":1113,":@":1158},[1114,1116,1157],{"#text":1115},"\n              ",{"tr":1117},[1118,1120,1126,1127,1132,1133,1138,1139,1144,1145,1150,1151,1156],{"#text":1119},"\n                ",{"th":1121,":@":1124},[1122],{"#text":1123},"Name",{"@_align":1125},"left",{"#text":1119},{"th":1128,":@":1131},[1129],{"#text":1130},"Country",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1134,":@":1137},[1135],{"#text":1136},"Population age range",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1140,":@":1143},[1141],{"#text":1142},"Provenance",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1146,":@":1149},[1147],{"#text":1148},"Start date—End date",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1152,":@":1155},[1153],{"#text":1154},"Number of patients",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":779},{"@_valign":1159},"top",{"#text":779},{"tbody":1162,":@":1324},[1163,1164,1202,1203,1240,1241,1279,1280,1323],{"#text":1115},{"tr":1165},[1166,1167,1172,1173,1177,1178,1183,1184,1189,1190,1195,1196,1201],{"#text":1119},{"td":1168,":@":1171},[1169],{"#text":1170},"IBM® MarketScan® Commercial Claims and Encounters (CCAE)",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1174,":@":1176},[1175],{"#text":475},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1179,":@":1182},[1180],{"#text":1181},"\u003C64 years",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1185,":@":1188},[1186],{"#text":1187},"Employer-sponsored commercial claims",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1191,":@":1194},[1192],{"#text":1193},"Jan 2000—December 2019",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1197,":@":1200},[1198],{"#text":1199},"173 M",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":1115},{"tr":1204},[1205,1206,1211,1212,1216,1217,1222,1223,1228,1229,1233,1234,1239],{"#text":1119},{"td":1207,":@":1210},[1208],{"#text":1209},"IBM® MarketScan® Medicare Supplemental Database (MDCR)",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1213,":@":1215},[1214],{"#text":475},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1218,":@":1221},[1219],{"#text":1220},"≥ 65 years",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1224,":@":1227},[1225],{"#text":1226},"Employer-sponsored Medicare claims",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1230,":@":1232},[1231],{"#text":1193},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1235,":@":1238},[1236],{"#text":1237},"11 M",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":1115},{"tr":1242},[1243,1244,1249,1250,1254,1255,1260,1261,1266,1267,1272,1273,1278],{"#text":1119},{"td":1245,":@":1248},[1246],{"#text":1247},"IBM® MarketScan® Multi-State Medicaid Database (MDCD)",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1251,":@":1253},[1252],{"#text":475},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1256,":@":1259},[1257],{"#text":1258},"0–90 years",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1262,":@":1265},[1263],{"#text":1264},"Medicaid claims",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1268,":@":1271},[1269],{"#text":1270},"Jan 2006—June 2019",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1274,":@":1277},[1275],{"#text":1276},"43 M",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":1115},{"tr":1281},[1282,1283,1294,1295,1299,1300,1304,1305,1310,1311,1316,1317,1322],{"#text":1119},{"td":1284,":@":1293},[1285,1287,1291],{"#text":1286},"Optum",{"sup":1288},[1289],{"#text":1290},"©",{"#text":1292}," De-Identified Clinformatics® Data Mart Database—Date of Death (Optum DOD)",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1296,":@":1298},[1297],{"#text":475},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1301,":@":1303},[1302],{"#text":1258},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1306,":@":1309},[1307],{"#text":1308},"Commercial claims",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1312,":@":1315},[1313],{"#text":1314},"May 2000—March 2020",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1318,":@":1321},[1319],{"#text":1320},"108 M",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":779},{"@_valign":1159},{"#text":738},{"#text":753},{"@_id":1066,"@_position":1328},"float",{"#text":753},{"p":1331},[1332],{"#text":1333},"The use of IBM MarketScan and Optum databases was reviewed by the New England Institutional Review Board (IRB) and were determined to be exempt from study-specific IRB approval.",{"#text":858},{"@_id":1044},{"#text":858},{"sec":1338,":@":1537},[1339,1340,1344,1345,1358,1359,1382,1383,1432,1433,1536],{"#text":753},{"title":1341},[1342],{"#text":1343},"2.2 Prediction task",{"#text":753},{"p":1346},[1347,1349,1356],{"#text":1348},"The aim of all predictive models in this study is to identify, among new users of warfarin or new users of DOACs with prior history of AF, the patients who will develop a MB event within 1–365 days after the first recorded dispensing of the medication of interest (i.e., the index date) (see ",{"xref":1350,":@":1353},[1351],{"#text":1352},"Figure 1",{"@_ref-type":1354,"@_rid":1355},"fig","F1",{"#text":1357},").",{"#text":753},{"fig":1360,":@":1381},[1361,1362,1366,1367,1375,1376,1380],{"#text":738},{"label":1363},[1364],{"#text":1365},"FIGURE 1",{"#text":738},{"caption":1368},[1369,1370,1374],{"#text":779},{"p":1371},[1372],{"#text":1373},"Diagram depicting the prediction of major bleeding events 1–365 days after index in patients with prior AF.",{"#text":738},{"#text":738},{"graphic":1377,":@":1378},[],{"@_xlink:href":1379},"fdsfr-02-1034677-g001.tif",{"#text":753},{"@_id":1355,"@_position":1328},{"#text":753},{"sec":1384,":@":1430},[1385,1386,1390,1391,1395,1396,1412,1413,1429],{"#text":738},{"title":1387},[1388],{"#text":1389},"2.2.1 Target populations",{"#text":738},{"p":1392},[1393],{"#text":1394},"The target populations used in this study consist of patients with a prior diagnosis of AF and no prior history of mitral valve stenosis.",{"#text":738},{"p":1397},[1398,1399,1403,1405,1411],{"#text":779},{"bold":1400},[1401],{"#text":1402},"Target population 1",{"#text":1404}," is new users of warfarin, including patients aged 18 years and older with new exposure to warfarin (1st date of dispensing was considered the index date) and at least 365 days database observation time prior to the index date, at tion 2 are provided as supplementary material and thee index date. The codes used for defining target population 1 are provided as supplementary material and theattrition tables are shown attrition tables are shown in ",{"xref":1406,":@":1409},[1407],{"#text":1408},"Table A1",{"@_ref-type":1065,"@_rid":1410},"TA1",{"#text":1090},{"#text":738},{"p":1414},[1415,1416,1420,1422,1428],{"#text":779},{"bold":1417},[1418],{"#text":1419},"Target population 2",{"#text":1421}," is new users of DOACs, including patients aged 18 years and older with new exposure to a DOAC (1st date of dispensing was considered index date) and at least 365 days database observation time prior to the index date, at least one prior diagnosis of AF, no prior mitral valve stenosis, and no exposure to warfarin all time prior to index date. The codes used for defining target population 2 are provided as supplementary material and the attrition tables are shown in ",{"xref":1423,":@":1426},[1424],{"#text":1425},"Table A2",{"@_ref-type":1065,"@_rid":1427},"TA2",{"#text":1090},{"#text":753},{"@_id":1431},"s2-2-1",{"#text":753},{"sec":1434,":@":1534},[1435,1436,1440,1441,1482,1483,1487,1488,1528,1529,1533],{"#text":738},{"title":1437},[1438],{"#text":1439},"2.2.2 Outcome definition",{"#text":738},{"p":1442},[1443,1445,1451,1452,1458,1460],{"#text":1444},"Major bleeding (MB) is the outcome of interest for this study; a clinical event of MB was mainly ascertained based on the Cunningham algorithm, which has been widely used in previous works (",{"xref":1446,":@":1449},[1447],{"#text":1448},"Cunningham et al., 2011",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":1450},"B2",{"#text":909},{"xref":1453,":@":1456},[1454],{"#text":1455},"Graham et al., 2015",{"@_ref-type":879,"@_rid":1457},"B7",{"#text":1459},"). Briefly, occurrence of a MB event was defined as.",{"list":1461,":@":1480},[1462,1468,1474],{"list-item":1463},[1464],{"p":1465},[1466],{"#text":1467},"1) a primary condition occurrence of definite bleeding during an inpatient visit, OR.",{"list-item":1469},[1470],{"p":1471},[1472],{"#text":1473},"2) a primary condition occurrence of excessive and frequent menstruation during an inpatient visit with a secondary condition occurrence of anemia or syncope during the same visit, OR.",{"list-item":1475},[1476],{"p":1477},[1478],{"#text":1479},"3) a primary condition occurrence of possible bleeding during an inpatient visit",{"@_list-type":1481},"simple",{"#text":738},{"p":1484},[1485],{"#text":1486},"With a secondary condition occurrence of definite bleeding during the same visit.",{"#text":738},{"p":1489},[1490,1492],{"#text":1491},"Upon identifying potential qualifying events, they must also comply with the following criteria to be considered outcome events:",{"list":1493,":@":1527},[1494,1500],{"list-item":1495},[1496],{"p":1497},[1498],{"#text":1499},"1) no trauma conditions, procedures, or observations during the same visit as the initial event. AND.",{"list-item":1501},[1502,1506],{"p":1503},[1504],{"#text":1505},"2) have one of the following:",{"list":1507,":@":1526},[1508,1514,1520],{"list-item":1509},[1510],{"p":1511},[1512],{"#text":1513},"a Death within 7 days following the index date,",{"list-item":1515},[1516],{"p":1517},[1518],{"#text":1519},"b At least 1 condition occurrence of a bleeding at a critical site during the same visit as the initial event",{"list-item":1521},[1522],{"p":1523},[1524],{"#text":1525},"c Any transfusion code during the same visit as the initial event",{"@_list-type":1481},{"@_list-type":1481},{"#text":738},{"p":1530},[1531],{"#text":1532},"The time-at-risk for MB events was from 1 day until 365 days after the new exposure to either warfarin (in target population 1) or a DOAC (in target population 2).",{"#text":753},{"@_id":1535},"s2-2-2",{"#text":858},{"@_id":1538},"s2-2",{"#text":858},{"sec":1541,":@":2647},[1542,1543,1547,1548,1572,1573,1585,1586,2635,2636,2646],{"#text":753},{"title":1544},[1545],{"#text":1546},"2.3 Validation of existing major bleeding prediction models",{"#text":753},{"p":1549},[1550,1552,1555,1557,1560,1561,1565,1567,1571],{"#text":1551},"In the current study, we first evaluated 5 existing MB prediction models: ORBIT, ATRIA, HAS-BLED, CHADS",{"sub":1553},[1554],{"#text":616},{"#text":1556},", and CHA",{"sub":1558},[1559],{"#text":616},{"#text":851},{"sub":1562},[1563],{"#text":1564},"2-",{"#text":1566},"VASc using the databases described in ",{"xref":1568,":@":1570},[1569],{"#text":1041},{"@_ref-type":1043,"@_rid":1044},{"#text":1090},{"#text":753},{"p":1574},[1575,1577,1583],{"#text":1576},"The existing models all include a limited number of covariates, summarized in ",{"xref":1578,":@":1581},[1579],{"#text":1580},"Table 2",{"@_ref-type":1065,"@_rid":1582},"T2",{"#text":1584},". Although the internal validation AUROC for some of the models was as high as 0.8, previous external validation of these models tends to achieve an AUROC between 0.6 and 0.7.",{"#text":753},{"table-wrap":1587,":@":2634},[1588,1589,1593,1594,1602,1603,2633],{"#text":738},{"label":1590},[1591],{"#text":1592},"TABLE 2",{"#text":738},{"caption":1595},[1596,1597,1601],{"#text":779},{"p":1598},[1599],{"#text":1600},"Existing models for predicting major bleeding risk.",{"#text":738},{"#text":738},{"table":1604},[1605,1606,1660,1661,2632],{"#text":779},{"thead":1607,":@":1659},[1608,1609,1658],{"#text":1115},{"tr":1610},[1611,1612,1615,1616,1621,1622,1627,1628,1633,1634,1642,1643,1657],{"#text":1119},{"th":1613,":@":1614},[],{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1617,":@":1620},[1618],{"#text":1619},"ORBIT",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1623,":@":1626},[1624],{"#text":1625},"ATRIA",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1629,":@":1632},[1630],{"#text":1631},"HAS-BLED",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1635,":@":1641},[1636,1638],{"#text":1637},"CHADS",{"sub":1639},[1640],{"#text":616},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"th":1644,":@":1656},[1645,1647,1650,1651,1654],{"#text":1646},"CHA",{"sub":1648},[1649],{"#text":616},{"#text":851},{"sub":1652},[1653],{"#text":616},{"#text":1655},"VASc",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":779},{"@_valign":1159},{"#text":779},{"tbody":1662,":@":2631},[1663,1664,1706,1707,1750,1751,1778,1779,1812,1813,1845,1846,1879,1880,1910,1911,1944,1945,1975,1976,2010,2011,2044,2045,2076,2077,2107,2108,2138,2139,2168,2169,2199,2200,2231,2232,2262,2263,2293,2294,2324,2325,2355,2356,2386,2387,2430,2431,2458,2459,2492,2493,2525,2526,2561,2562,2593,2594,2630],{"#text":1115},{"tr":1665},[1666,1667,1677,1678,1683,1684,1689,1690,1695,1696,1700,1701,1705],{"#text":1119},{"td":1668,":@":1676},[1669,1671,1675],{"#text":1670},"\n                  ",{"bold":1672},[1673],{"#text":1674},"Type of Data",{"#text":1119},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1679,":@":1682},[1680],{"#text":1681},"Registry",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1685,":@":1688},[1686],{"#text":1687},"Electronic Health Records",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1691,":@":1694},[1692],{"#text":1693},"Clinical Trial",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1697,":@":1699},[1698],{"#text":1681},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1702,":@":1704},[1703],{"#text":1681},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":1115},{"tr":1708},[1709,1710,1719,1720,1725,1726,1731,1732,1737,1738,1743,1744,1749],{"#text":1119},{"td":1711,":@":1718},[1712,1713,1717],{"#text":1670},{"bold":1714},[1715],{"#text":1716},"Cohort Size",{"#text":1119},{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1721,":@":1724},[1722],{"#text":1723},"7,411",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1727,":@":1730},[1728],{"#text":1729},"13,559",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1733,":@":1736},[1734],{"#text":1735},"7,329",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1739,":@":1742},[1740],{"#text":1741},"1,733",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1119},{"td":1745,":@":1748},[1746],{"#text":1747},"1,577",{"@_align":1125},{"#text":1115},{"#text":1115},{"tr":1752},[1753,1754,1757,1758,1761,1762